---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="Lab · Fran Canete">
  <main>
    <section id="lab" class="section-hero-personal">
      <div class="container">
        <span class="hero-personal-role">03 / Lab · Side projects</span>

        <h1 class="page-title">What I built, what I <em>learned.</em></h1>

        <div class="page-meta">
          <span class="kind">02 case studies</span>
          <span class="sep">·</span>
          <span>Both live in production</span>
          <span class="sep">·</span>
          <span>Updated Apr 2026</span>
        </div>

        <p class="hero-bio" style="max-width: 720px; margin: 0">
          Two production AI SaaS apps and the lessons I'm still digesting.
          Each one taught me something I couldn't have picked up from a
          tutorial — about LLMs, about scale, about the gap between "it works"
          and "it ships." The "What I learned" sections matter more than the
          stack lists.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="lab-list">
          <!-- Planitly -->
          <article class="lab-case">
            <header class="lab-case-head">
              <div class="left">
                <span class="num">01</span>
                <h2>Planitly.</h2>
              </div>
              <div class="right">
                <a href="https://planitly.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">planitly.com →</a>
                <span class="sep">·</span>
                <span>Launched 2024</span>
                <span class="sep">·</span>
                <span class="status">Live</span>
              </div>
            </header>
            <p class="lab-lead">
              AI-powered travel planning SaaS that generates personalized
              multi-day vacation itineraries using OpenAI GPT-4o, validated
              against TripAdvisor for real-world bookable activities.
            </p>

            <div class="lab-detail">
              <div class="highlights">
                <span class="label">
                  <span>Highlights</span><span class="count">03 / many</span>
                </span>
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    <span class="n">01</span>
                    <span>Two-phase AI generation: Zod-validated structured outputs, then TripAdvisor resolution in parallel.</span>
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <span class="n">02</span>
                    <span>Event-driven Inngest workflow — 11-step async job with retries and transactional commits.</span>
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <span class="n">03</span>
                    <span>16 Sequelize models, 74 migrations, 34 API endpoints. Complex relational schema, multi-provider auth.</span>
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <div class="stack">
                <span class="label">
                  <span>Stack</span><span class="count">19 items</span>
                </span>
                <div class="chips">
                  <span class="chip chip-sm">Next.js 14</span>
                  <span class="chip chip-sm">TypeScript</span>
                  <span class="chip chip-sm">MUI v6</span>
                  <span class="chip chip-sm">PostgreSQL</span>
                  <span class="chip chip-sm">Inngest</span>
                  <span class="chip chip-sm">OpenAI GPT-4o</span>
                  <span class="chip chip-sm">Stripe</span>
                  <span class="mono-text" style="align-self: center; padding-left: 4px">+12</span>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="lab-learned">
              <span class="label">What I learned</span>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Structured outputs (Zod schemas) changed everything.
                  Free-text JSON is a debugging nightmare; schema-validated is
                  night-and-day.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Background jobs are non-negotiable for LLM workflows.
                  Anything &gt; 5s needs Inngest, a queue, or you'll fight
                  Vercel timeouts forever.
                </li>
                <li>
                  I over-engineered the database too early. Half those 16
                  models could've started as JSONB columns. Schema-shape your
                  data <em>after</em> you know how it's queried.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </article>

          <!-- Duebase -->
          <article class="lab-case">
            <header class="lab-case-head">
              <div class="left">
                <span class="num">02</span>
                <h2>Duebase.</h2>
              </div>
              <div class="right">
                <a href="https://duebase.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">duebase.com →</a>
                <span class="sep">·</span>
                <span>Launched 2025</span>
                <span class="sep">·</span>
                <span class="status">Live</span>
              </div>
            </header>
            <p class="lab-lead">
              AI-powered financial due diligence on UK Companies House
              filings. Risk scores and health assessments in 30 seconds using
              Gemini 2.5 Flash with structured JSON output.
            </p>

            <div class="lab-detail">
              <div class="highlights">
                <span class="label">
                  <span>Highlights</span><span class="count">03 / many</span>
                </span>
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    <span class="n">01</span>
                    <span>Gemini 2.5 Flash with structured JSON output — 40+ financial metrics extracted per filing.</span>
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <span class="n">02</span>
                    <span>Real-time search across 15M+ UK companies. Mapper pattern + parallel filing-history sync.</span>
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <span class="n">03</span>
                    <span>Daily payment reconciliation across Stripe and LemonSqueezy. Cron jobs that catch the things webhooks miss.</span>
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <div class="stack">
                <span class="label">
                  <span>Stack</span><span class="count">20 items</span>
                </span>
                <div class="chips">
                  <span class="chip chip-sm">Next.js 14</span>
                  <span class="chip chip-sm">TypeScript</span>
                  <span class="chip chip-sm">MUI v7</span>
                  <span class="chip chip-sm">Sequelize</span>
                  <span class="chip chip-sm">Gemini 2.5</span>
                  <span class="chip chip-sm">Inngest</span>
                  <span class="chip chip-sm">Stripe</span>
                  <span class="mono-text" style="align-self: center; padding-left: 4px">+13</span>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="lab-learned">
              <span class="label">What I learned</span>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Gemini 2.5 Flash with structured outputs is shockingly good
                  at financial document parsing — and an order of magnitude
                  cheaper than GPT-4o for this workload.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Payment reconciliation is its own product. Two providers,
                  three race conditions, one cron job. Worth getting right
                  before you have paying users, not after.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Trial systems live or die by lifecycle logic. The 14-day
                  reset cost me a week of bugs that only production traffic
                  could've surfaced.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </article>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>
